<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Judiciary Chairman Defends Senate on Judgeship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Faced with criticism by the
president and the chief justice of the U.S. Supreme Court about
the Senate's slow pace in confirming federal judges, the chairman
of the Senate Judiciary Committee defended the Senate's performance
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"There are many parties who have a role in these problems,"
Senator Orrin Hatch, a Republican, was quoted as saying in The New
York Times Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The No. 1 problem happens to be activist judges who continue
to find laws that aren't there and expand the law beyond the
intent of Congress,"
</P>
<P>
Hatch disagreed with complaints about overworked judges,
saying, "There is little or no room to complain."
</P>
<P>
In the past year Democrats and Republicans spent much time
arguing over judicial nominations.
</P>
<P>
In his year-end report on the federal judiciary earlier this
week, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist blamed the Senate for
"serious delays in the appointment process."
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist said 82 of 846 federal judgeships remain vacant, and
26 of those vacancies have existed for 18 months or longer.
</P>
<P>
He said such a high level of vacancies cannot continue "without
eroding the quality of justice that traditionally has been
associated with the federal judiciary."
</P>
<P>
The White House officials, citing the report, said the judicial
system is more important than "playing partisan politics."
</P>
<P>
But Hatch argued that the Republican-controlled Senate
confirmed 36 of the 47 judicial nominees it considered last year.
He blamed President Bill Clinton for being slow in naming
candidates.
</P>
<P>
Responding to Rehnquist's report, Hatch said Congress could
work to address the concerns and address the selection progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
