<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Court Paves Way for IRA Suspect Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A court in London cleared the way
early today for an Irish Republican Army (IRA) suspect to be
extradited to Germany on bombing charges.
</P>
<P>
Magistrate Nicholas Evans ruled that 26-year-old Roisin
McAliskey await the decision of British Home Secretary Jack Straw
on whether she should be extradited to Germany.
</P>
<P>
"In the particular circumstances of this case, bearing in mind
McAliskey's state of health, I now commit her in her absence to
await the decision of the Secretary of State (Jack Straw) about
her extradition to Germany," Evans said.
</P>
<P>
McAliskey, who was arrested in November 1996, is being held in
a London psychiatric hospital with her baby daughter and
McAliskey's mother said her daughter has been too ill to attend
court hearings.
</P>
<P>
The German government has been demanding McAliskey's
extradition on suspicion of her involvement in a June 1996 IRA
bomb attack on a British Army Base at Osnabrueck, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Irish government, which made diplomatic
representations to Germany about the case, has called for her
release on humanitarian grounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
