<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Establishes Education Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A 12-member commmission tasked
with reviewing Zimbabwe's education and training system was sworn
in today by President Robert Mugabe at State House in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The commission, chaired by University of Zimbabwe professor
Caiphas Nziramasanga is the first to be appointed since the
country's independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
A review of Zimbabwe's education was last held in 1962 and
with the on-going technological advances coupled with changing
industry requirements, there is now need to check the system for
relevance.
</P>
<P>
Education, Sport and Culture Minister Gabriel Machinga said
education is dynamic, and it is important that it be reviewed
periodically to ensure it is in line with set goals.
</P>
<P>
''Consideration of the basic principles and philosophy of
Zimbabwe's educational and training needs and aspirations on the
eve of the 21st century, and having regard to the challenges of a
competitive global environment in the information age,'' the
terms of reference for the commission said.
</P>
<P>
The commission, comprising educationists, representatives of
industry and teachers' associations, is mandated with
establishing an appropriate framework for the organization and
management of the education and training systems.
</P>
<P>
The commission has two external members, Roy Pryke, an
international and comparative education consultant based in
Britain and Jacques Hallak of the Paris-based International
Institute of Educational planning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
