<HEADLINE> Pollution in Kathmandu Threatens Children's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Air pollution in Kathmandu has
emerged as a major health hazard for children, experts said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
They told a seminar that 2,674 children under the age of 14
from the urban areas of Kathmandu were admitted to hospital with
respiratory problems in the fiscal year 1996-97 which ended on
July 14, 1997, Nepal's official RSS news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Air pollution is most serious at school-going time in the
morning and after 3 p.m. when children return from school, the RSS
quoted the experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the seminar jointly held by Leaders Nepal, a
non-governmental organization, and the Hino-Social Education
Center of Japan, Nepali Health Minister Bipin Koirala said the
government is worried about the deteriorating environment of the
country.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for the government and national and
international organizations to resolve the problem in an
integrated manner.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth in population and vehicles, among others, is
blamed for the deteriorating environment in Kathmandu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
