<HEADLINE> S. African College Trains Sign Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The University of the Free
State in South Africa is training sign language interpreters to help
communication with disabled South Africans.
</P>
<P>
The university's community interpreter program said the training
sessions focused on interpreting where language and cultural
differences had to be bridged, South African Press Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
About a tenth of South Africans had one or other degree of
disability and four percent of these people depended on signs as
their first language, said the program of the university, located
in Bloemfontein, capital of Free State.
</P>
<P>
Groups from all over the country are attending the training
classes, which are offered jointly by the university and the
National Association for the Deaf in South Africa, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
