<HEADLINE> Water Borne Diseases Hit Flooded Areas in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Water borne diseases have
broken out in southern Somalia as the heavy rains are still
afflicting the areas neighboring the border lines between
Somalia, Kenya and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the southern town of Dhobley today said more than
40 people have died and dozens of others are in critical
condition from two major diseases that broke out in the town
early in the week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a reliable source in Dhobley, 19 of
these people have died of a new unknown sickness.
</P>
<P>
The source said seven more people suffering from very high
fever and vomiting blood are still in the town which lacks all
medical services.
</P>
<P>
The town of Dhobley, about 250 km southwest of the port town
of Kismaio, remains isolated from the main towns following the
heavy rains and floods that ruined almost all of the roads since
October last year.
</P>
<P>
Muse Khalif Omar, a community leader also in Dhobley Town,
said that cholera has killed 21 people in the town in the past
five days.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the border town of Dhobley, there are other reports
of deaths for the mysterious disease in the town of Liboye also
close to the border with Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, more than 34 people have died so far
from blood vomiting and high fever in the past two weeks in the
region. Doctors in the town of Kismaio, 500 km south of
Mogadishu, confirmed nine cases of this new disease in the town
hospital.
</P>
<P>
The same mysterious disease still claimed lives in Jalalaqsi
town of Hiran region, 150 km north of the capital. The District
Commissioner of the town, Abdulkadir Arif Gure, said 39 people
have died of this unidentified sickness since December 25.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities in Somalia believe that this mysterious
disease has crossed the border from Kenya into Somalia. The first
area where the sickness was seen is the village of Torotorow, 115
km south of Mogadishu, where more than 45 people have died of the
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
