<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ulster Police Chief Warns of More Bloodshed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Chief Constable
Ronnie Flanagan warned early today that Northern Ireland could
face more bloodshed after a series of killings over the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after holding crisis talks with British
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam, Flanagan said that the Royal
Ulster Constabulary is putting more police patrols in a bid to
prevent further attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We've had dreadful murders in recent days and sadly I cannot
say that that's the last murder that we're going to witness,"
Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mowlam has urged all sides to "keep
things in perspective" ahead of multi-party peace talks which are
due to reopen in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
However, Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble said that
the recent violence has cast deep doubts over the validity of the
Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
"There is a danger that the actions of the Loyalist Volunteer
Force will lead to a crumbling of the ceasefire," he said.
</P>
<P>
The latest escalation of Ulster violence began on Saturday with
the assassination of pro-British loyalist prisoner Billy Wright in
Belfast's high-security Maze prison.
</P>
<P>
In response, a pro-British group, the Loyalist Volunteer Force
(LVF), retaliated by killing two men including a hotel doorman, a
former Irish Republican Army (IRA) guerilla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
