<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Communist Party Calls for Referendum on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The French Communist Party (PCF)
National Secretary Robert Hue today called for a referendum on the
Amsterdam treaty, which predicts the construction of an integrated
Europe in political, social and economic fields.
</P>
<P>
Hue also asked President Jacques Chirac to meet him on the
issue as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The PCF made the proposal after the French Constitutional
Council announced on Wednesday that the adoption of the Amsterdam
treaty needs a constitutional amendment beforehand.
</P>
<P>
"In France, it is the people, and they only, who carry out the
national sovereignty... It is natural that it comes back to the
people to declare through a universal suffrage," said Hue in a
published declaration.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac will either call for a referendum or a joint
congress of the two chambers of the parliament to vote for the
constitutional amendment in order to adopt the Amsterdam treaty.
</P>
<P>
It is more likely that Chirac, who himself is an advocate of
European integration, will choose a joint congress of parliament
deputies because both the National Assembly and the Senate have a
majority of deputies who support the Amsterdam treaty.
</P>
<P>
Former President Francois Mitterrand chose to hold a referendum
on September 20, 1992, to decide whether France should amend its
constitution to sign the Maastricht treaty, an earlier version of
Amsterdam treaty.
</P>
<P>
The PCF has already decided to organize a demonstration on
January 18 in Paris to urge a referendum on the European single
currency euro.
</P>
<P>
"Because it concerns the future of the Frenchmen and
Frenchwomen, we affirm that they should be really informed about
which is being prepared today far from them and without them,"
said Hue.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled that Chirac promised to organize a referendum
on European integration in November 1994, before the May 1995
presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
