<HEADLINE> Girl Condemned for Street Violence in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- An 18-year-old girl was condemned
today to 18 months in jail by a court in Strasbourg for
participating in an attempt to burn a vehicle on New Year's eve,
reported Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
Cindia Supplon, who was an apprentice of tapestry weaving,
admitted breaking the window of a car of her neighbor's.
</P>
<P>
Her two accomplice, two minors under 18, will be tried in a
court for children for having tried to burn the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three vehicles were burnt on New Year's eve in Strasbourg
by teenagers rampaging through all the rough districts of the
capital of Alsace.
</P>
<P>
The riot has caused a dispute between the public prosecutor of
Bas-Rhin, Magistrate Edmond Stenger, and local police chief
Patrice Magner.
</P>
<P>
Stenger blamed police for lack of efficiency in maintaining
public order, while Magner said that to prevent the riot, one
needed "5,000 agents or a curfew." 
</P>
</TEXT>
