<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mowlam Says British Army to Patrol Belfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- British Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam announced here today that British army foot
patrols will return to Belfast in an effort to maintain social
order and prevent further violence.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam was quoted by the BBC radio as saying that the situation
in Northern Ireland was serious but not out of control.
</P>
<P>
She noted that increased security measures would include the
"return of foot patrols with the army in Belfast." Army foot
patrols were lifted only some weeks ago as an significant step of
building confidence.
</P>
<P>
Early today, Northern Ireland Chief Constable Ronnie Flanagan
warned that Northern Ireland could face more bloodshed after a
series of killings over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The latest escalation of Ulster violence began on Saturday with
the assassination of pro-British loyalist prisoner Billy Wright in
Belfast's high-security Maze prison.
</P>
<P>
In response, a pro-British group, the Loyalist Volunteer Force
(LVF), retaliated by killing two men including a hotel doorman, a
former Irish Republican Army (IRA) guerilla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
