<HEADLINE> Privatization to Earn Mozambique $210 Million in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Investment
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Privatization of state-owned
enterprises will bring about 210 million U.S. dollars in
investment for Mozambique in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Momad Juma, Head of the Technical Unit of Enterprise
Restructure of Mozambique (UTRE), said this in Maputo today,
quoted by the News Agency of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's privatization started in 1987. By early last
December, 846 out of the 1,254 registered state-owned enterprises
had been privatized.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 17 large state-owned enterprises and all the medium
and small-sized enterprises are expected to be privatized, Juma
said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that with the help of the Commonwealth, the UTRE
is carrying out a study on the impact of privatization on
Mozambique's Gross Demostic Production, employment, tax and other
aspects of the social life.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican nationals have benefitted more
from the privatization than foreigners, as 90 percent of the
enterprises were sold to natives compared with 10 percent to
foreigners, Momad Juma said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
