<HEADLINE> Christmas Holiday Road Deaths Cost S. Africa $41 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The death toll on South
African roads has risen to 729 since December 1, 1997, costing
the country about 200 million Rand (40.6 million U.S. Dollars),
the South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figures represented a sharp drop from the fatalities and
hence the cost in the same period last year, South Africa's
national road safety "Arrive Alive" campaign said. In December,
1996, 1,047 people died in traffic accidents, resulting in a cost
of 286 million Rand (59.6 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The majority of road users did a fantastic job so far this
year. Drivers displayed a much better attitude," the campaign's
spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Traffic was expected to start increasing countrywide from this
weekend, when many holiday-makers return to work from resorts.
The traffic flow will probably peak next weekend, on January 10
and 11.
</P>
<P>
The campaign attributed the accidents mainly to speeding and
alcohol abuse. It called on drivers to ensure they were rested
and their vehicles were roadworthy. 
</P>
