<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Makes Efforts to Defuse Budget Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to defuse deepening
crisis over the state budget of 1998, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said today that he planed to live up to his
promises to Foreign Minister David Levy on the budget.
</P>
<P>
At a reception in Tel Aviv, Netanyahu said that efforts had
been made to find funds to meet Levy's demands, which included
further aid by the government to development towns and
underprivileged neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, Netanyahu also expressed confidence
today that he will be able to get the approval of the budget in
the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The Knesset is expected to reconvene on Monday to vote on the
second and third readings of both the budget and its accompanying
economic arrangements bill.
</P>
<P>
Levy threatened on Thursday to resign if his demands are not
met. A close confidant of his said today that he had already
written a letter of resignation and planed to submit it to the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A report of Israel Radio said that Netanyahu would do all he
can in order not to lose Levy, whose five-member Gesher party is
crucial for the passage of the budget in the Knesset as well as
the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office in a statement said the next two
days will be used to "arrive at a budget agreed upon by the prime
minister and the foreign minister."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Knesset Speaker Dan Tichon said the crisis over the
budget can be resolved very easily. He claimed that there are
budget reserves to meet Levy's demands since many ministries did
not spend their entire budget allocation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman threatened to resign if
Netanyahu gives in to Levy's demands, which he said could break
the current budget framework.
</P>
<P>
Neeman had promised that no tax be levied to meet coalition
parties' demands and the 1998 budget deficit be reduce to less
than 2.4 percent of the gross domestic product. 
</P>
