<HEADLINE> 25 Awaiting-Trial Prisoners Escape in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- An awaiting-trial prisoner
freed 24 of his colleagues Thursday night from a police cell in
South Africa's Mpumalanga Province, South African Press
Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The prisoner, held at a cell near Marble Hall, some 150
kilometers northeast of Pretoria, made off with a policeman's
pistol and the cell keys at a shebeen.
</P>
<P>
None of the escapees have been re-arrested by this evening.
</P>
<P>
Police have launched a massive manhunt and an internal inquiry
into the escape of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Doep du Plooy said, a police sergeant at the
Kwa-Mhlanga police station took two prisoners from the cells at
about 9 p.m. (1900 GMT) to a nearby shebeen where they ate and
drank.
</P>
<P>
The exact circumstances in which the prisoner got hold of the
policeman's gun and the cell keys were not known.
</P>
<P>
The sergeant was arrested at his home this morning and an
urgent manhunt and internal investigation has been launched, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Du Plooy said the policeman could face charges of aiding and
abetting the escape of a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
Prison escapes in South Africa are frequent, a large number of
which involved cooperation from wardens.
</P>
<P>
More than 900 prisoners escaped from police or court cells
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
