<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Sees Poverty as Top Cause for Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) has identified poverty as the greatest single
cause that creates child labor.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty forces many children to work full time for their own
and their families's survival," the United Nations agency ILO
says in a document reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The document said, poverty, which is the acute need of many
households to keep family members working to ensure income
security, has made it nearly impossible for people to invest in
their children's education.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions, noted the ILO, have a key role to play in
combating the menace by carrying out their basic objectives of
negotiating increased wages, jobs and improved working conditions
as well as stop discriminations of any sort as far as employment
is concerned.
</P>
<P>
If these are done, it said, the effective means will be
achieved to realize the potentials in the struggle against child
labor.
</P>
<P>
The agency, however, adds that the capacity of the unions to
perceive and respond to the problem of child labor depends on
their level of organization, a major problem facing developing
countries, where much of child labor is found.
</P>
<P>
Countries including Nigeria, Kenya, Niger, Algeria, Brazil,
Italy and Cuba have child labor, according to the ILO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
