<HEADLINE> Kenyan Political Leaders Advised to Accept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Electoral Commission
today requested political leaders in the country to accept the
final results of the December 29-30 general elections to be
announced soon.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here, the commission asked Kenyan
leaders "not to adopt the attitude that they would support the
results only if they are going to win but reject the results if
they are likely to lose."
</P>
<P>
The commission today announced official results of the
presidential election in 126 out of 210 constituencies, saying
that incumbent President Daniel arap Moi has garnered 1,538,116
votes to be followed by Mwai Kibaki with 1,276,096 votes and
Raila Odinga with 456,946 votes.
</P>
<P>
Noting that voting in presidential and parliamentary elections
had been conducted in all parts of the country, the statement
said, "no single constituency has reported failing to proceed
with the elections."
</P>
<P>
The ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) today accused
opposition leaders of hypocrisy for threatening to reject the
results of the elections to be announced within a few days.
</P>
<P>
KANU Vice-Chairman George Saitoti said at a news conference
today that "the will of the people has been expressed through the
ballot, and all those concerned should accept the verdict of the
people."
</P>
<P>
"However, it is extremely regrettable that some opposition
party leaders have displayed remarkable hypocrisy by threatening
chaos even before the results are announced," he added.
</P>
<P>
Two leading opposition presidential candidates said today that
they rejected preliminary results which showed President Moi
would win the elections.
</P>
<P>
Raila Odinga of National Development Party and Mwai Kibaki of
Democratic Party said at a joint press conference here this
afternoon that they categorically rejected the provisional
results of the presidential elections and called for a new
election within 21 days.
</P>
<P>
Based on unofficial latest results from 188 out of 210
constituencies, Moi headed the poll with 2.226 million votes, to
be followed by Kibaki with 1.761 million votes and Odinga with
622,660 votes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
