<HEADLINE> Cyprus Issue Should Be Solved Peaceful: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A Cypriot government spokesman
said here today that the Cyprus issue should be resolved
peacefully, adding, however, Cyprus is ready to confront Turkish
aggression in the framework of a defense pact with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Manolis Christofides was
commenting on the possibility of an incident in the area as ties
between Turkey and Greece were strained after the European Union
(EU) decided last month to start accession negotiations in March
1998.
</P>
<P>
Six countries, including Cyprus, fall into the first group of
candidates for EU enlargement, but Turkey falls out.
</P>
<P>
Angered by the EU decision, the Turkey-backed Turkish Cypriot
regime in northern Cyprus decided to suspend bicommunal contacts
since last Saturday in reprisal.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said "each country has its own defense
authorities who say they are ready to face any possibility if
another country, in our case Turkey, opts for an unacceptable
offensive policy."
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore not an issue that depends on us but on
Turkey, if it choses to follow an aggressive policy," the
spokesman stressed.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to Turkey to take note of international reaction and
chose a policy that would secure its European course," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey sent its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
