<HEADLINE> 44 Containers of Medicine Arrive in Iraq from UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A Cypriot container ship with 44
containers of medicines aboard arrived Thursday at Umm Al-Kasr
port, Basra in southern Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The medicines are the second batch of assistance from the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) to Iraq, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The consignment is a gift from Sheikh Muhammad Bin-Rashid
al-Maktoum, crown prince of Dubai and UAE minister of defense, to
the Iraqi people and children as a sign of solidarity between the
Iraqi and the UAE peoples in the face of the seven-year-old
U.N. embargoes on Iraq, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment of the UAE assistance arrived at the harbor
on December 6 with 31 containers of medicine on board.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, a team of UAE youths organized several direct
voyages to the harbor aboard "Al-Rahmah" (Grace) cruiser to
deliver a consignment of powdered milk and clothes to the Iraqi
children.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is still suffering from a severe shortage of foodstuffs
and medicines due to the U.N. sanctions imposed after its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was banned from exporting oil, its economic mainstay,
under the U.N. sanctions, which can not be lifted unless it is
certified to have destroyed all weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
