<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Rights Activists Shocked by US Release of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIGALI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- "We were shocked to hear the
release of Pastor Elizaphan Ntakirutimana by a federal judge" in
the U.S., a Rwandan human rights activist told Rwanda News Agency
today.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Ntakirutimana is not a war criminal as reported in the
media," Josue kayijaho, chairman of CLADHO, the umbrella
organization regrouping local human rights NGOs, stressed here,
adding, "He is a genocidalist because it was not a war he was
involved in here, but genocide."
</P>
<P>
According to Kayijaho, Ntakirutimana was a ring-leader in the
bloodshed that claimed the lives of over 100,000 followers who
had fled to his Nugonero 7th Day Adventist church when the
massacre of Tutsis started in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that this adventist clergyman was very much
trusted by people in western Rwanda's Kibuye region which was
inhabited by an estimated 250,000 Tutsis before the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
"Every body rushed to his church hoping to find protection
from marauding Hutu extremists," said a survivor who asked not to
be named.
</P>
<P>
The survivor noted that after three days of starvation in the
church where the pastor was himself residing, the displaced wrote
a letter asking him to provide them with relief food aid.
</P>
<P>
"In two hours," the pastor calmed the hungry people by saying,
"food aid will get to you."
</P>
<P>
According to various testimonies, after the said two hours,
pastor Ntakirutimana came back with his pick-up full of policemen
who started killing Tutsis at Mugonero Church.
</P>
<P>
It is further reported that on the first Sabbath that followed
the killings in his church, Ntakirutimana gathered the militiamen
and said, "Let 's pray because we have exterminated our enemies."
</P>
<P>
Among the killers was his own son, Gerard Ntakirutimana who,
during the genocide, was using a submachine-gun and kept an
important stock of ammunition for Hutu extremists provided by
Clement Kayishema, the former Governor of Kibuye. Both men are
currently detained in the U.N. Tribunal's prison in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The pastor continued to abet and perpetrate massacres of
Tutsis who managed to seek refuge in Bisesero Hills where they
organized a staunch resistance against the former Rwandan
presidential guards, government soldiers, the police, and the
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
the massacres of up to 800,000 Tutsis were staged in
retaliation for the downing of an airplane that killed 10 Rwandan
and Burundi officials including the then Hutu President J.
Habyarimana, the chief of staff of the Rwandan armed forces and
the Burundi president.
</P>
<P>
Returning from a regional summit in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
the plane was fired on, above Kigali airport, and exploded on
landing. That touched off tribal killings in the small central
African country.
</P>
<P>
"Out of 60,000 people who reached Bisesero, only 1,300 were
rescued when the Rwandan Patriotic Army and the French soldiers
of the Turquoise Operation later arrived in the area," Kayijaho
said.
</P>
<P>
"No single woman, no child survived the vicious attacks on
Bisesero; only strong men resisted," he underlined, blaming the
tragedy on pastor Ntakirutimana.
</P>
<P>
Among the people who perished at Mugonero Church were over 30
adventist pastors, and Ntakirutimana's personal friends.
</P>
<P>
His release on December 17, 1997 by Judge Marcel Notzon of
Lardo, Texas in the U.S., where Ntakirutimana was detained, came
as a surprise as his transfer to the U.N. Tribunal in Arusha had
been announced.
</P>
<P>
Judge Notzon blasted charges of Ntakirutimana's involvement in
the genocide of Tutsis in Kibuye, and claimed that the federal
government had no right to extradite him to the U.N. Court.
</P>
<P>
"This judge is part of negationists found in many places and
who continue to deny that genocide took place in Rwanda,"
Kayijaho pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Well informed sources told Rwanda News Agency that there are
very powerful lobbies in the U.S. behind the release of the
wanted criminal.
</P>
<P>
It is said that these lobbies are manipulated by Eliel
Ntakirutimana, the pastor's son, who settled in the U.S. in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon the U.S. administration to do all in its power
to have this genocide criminal brought to book for heinous crimes
he committed in Rwanda," kayijaho declared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
