<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dance Poem Presents Hong Kong's History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- "Fragrance: a Dance Poem on
Hong Kong" was staged here Saturday night, with some 400 dancers
presenting a 100-year chronicle of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The brainchild of 12 choreographers, the dance poem charted the
ups and downs of Hong Kong's fortune in eight scenes, featuring
significant aspects of Hong Kong's history such as Japanese
occupation, water rationing and the historic handover.
</P>
<P>
The dancers came from the Association of Hongkong Dance
Organizations, established in 1992 with 31 member organizations
and over 5,000 individual members.
</P>
<P>
Chan Hei-hing, chairman of the association, said, the idea of
creating a dance celebrating 1997, a very important year for Hong
Kong, was brewing in the association as early as 1995.
</P>
<P>
They had visited many sites across Hong Kong and gathered
information on local customs and traditions. "Finally, the theme
of the dance was set: that should be a testimony of the hard
working spirit and strife of the Hong Kong people over the last
century," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
It is called a dance poem because the dance is made up of a
succession of independent scenes without a central cast or a story
line.
</P>
<P>
Renowned composer Yip Shun-chi wrote the music for the
production but he passed away in September 1997 before the show
materialized on stage.
</P>
<P>
In parallel with the dance, presented on Saturday and Sunday at
the Hong Kong Cultural Center, a small exhibition entitled One
Hundred Faces in a Hong Kong Century -- a hundred-year chronicle
of Hong Kong fashion was held at the venue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
