<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A three-carriage hospital
train donated by the Hong Kong people has helped more than 600
blind people in China's remote areas restore eyesight since its
operation in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Nellie Fong, chairman of the Executive Committee of the
project, said this when announcing a charity show of a Golden
Harvest film -- a Jackie Chan movie "Who Am I" to raise funds for
the operation of the hospital train here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed as "Lifeline Express", the hospital train left Hong Kong
on July 1, last year on a special mission to provide free cataract
operations for the needy in those areas.
</P>
<P>
The presentation of the hospital train to China's inland areas
was officiated by Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region on that day.
</P>
<P>
Fong noted that there are now millions of blind people in
China's inland areas due to cataracts, adding that the "Lifeline
Express" will make use of the railway system to shuttle amongst
China's remote areas to provide free treatment to them.
</P>
<P>
She urged more Hong Kong people to donate generously to support
this meaningful hospital train project.  
