<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Make Holograms of Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have produced
holograms of cells by using a kind of X-ray as a light source and
putting the three-dimensional images of the holograms into
computers.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough was made at the University of Science and
Technology of China (USTC) which is based in Hefei, capital of
East China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
Scientists found that X-rays with a wavelength between 2.3 and
4.4 nanometers can pass through the water in cells but fails to
penetrate other substances.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at USTC drew the X-ray, called a "soft" X-ray, from
a synchro-cyclotron and made holograms of cells from onions and
fly wings, in which they could clearly see the cell nucleus, walls
and intercellular spaces.
</P>
<P>
Similar research has been carried out in the United States,
France and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Xie Xingshu, the professor in charge of research, said that
"Soft X-ray holography" may help biologists realize their dream of
observing a living cell's internal structure and activities.
</P>
<P>
Xie said the experiment should be improved by keeping the cells
alive through making changes in their experimental environment and
raising the X-ray's brightness to shorten the exposure time.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at USTC are now trying to get more precise
holograms for microstructure in cells such as chromosomes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0045 </DOCNO>
