<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai on Course to Power China's Economic Locomotive (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Expansion of the service sector, which now accounts for 45
percent of the city's total GDP (300 billion yuan in 1997), is one
of the major factors fueling rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
As part of its efforts to regain past glory as Asia's financial
center, Shanghai has established a comprehensive banking network
that involves financial institutions from home and abroad, trust
corporations and insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has become a hub for commodities, capital, technology,
information and intellectuals. Burgeoning markets of production
materials and commodity exchanges stimulate circulation while the
stock market, inter-bank lending and the foreign exchange trading
center enjoy brisk business.
</P>
<P>
Through economic restructuring, the city has also nurtured six
technology-intensive pillar industries including automobiles and
telecommunications as well as burgeoning industries such as
electronics and biological engineering.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other parts of China, most of the financially troubled
state-owned firms in Shanghai have been rescued and have become
vigorous through the introduction of a modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The continuous upsurge in overseas investment and an influx of
the world's leading conglomerates are also forces propelling rapid
growth. More than half of the top 100 multinational corporations
have offices in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
