<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Private Sector Contributes More Money in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Private and individual
businesses in Shanghai have contributed a record 2.8 billion yuan
(33.7 million U.S. dollars) to the city in taxes for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The sum is up 27 percent, or 600 million yuan (72 million
U.S. dollars), over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has more than 200,000 private and individual
businesses, up 20 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city has levied nearly one billion yuan (120 million
U.S. dollars) in taxes from private firms, most of which are
located in the outskirts of the city alone. The figure makes up 58
percent of the total taxation from the city's privately owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
Individual businesses in the urban area contributed 840 million
yuan to Shanghai's tax revenue in 1997, or 75 percent of
Shanghai's total for individually owned companies.
</P>
<P>
Taxes from the sector reached 260 million yuan in 1997, an
increase of 24 percent. The earnings tax on private businesses
climbed 38 percent to 120 million yuan; while, income taxes
collected from private and individual businessmen grew 24
percent to 80 million yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
