<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Activities to Care for Elderly, Young </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Activities urging people to show
respect for the aged and take good care of the young have been
launched across China as January, designated a "Special Month for
Caring for the Aged and the Young."
</P>
<P>
Free medical services and consultations for the elderly at the
China Women's Activities Center in the Chinese capital initiated
the special month today, which was launched by the All-China
Women's Federation.
</P>
<P>
Doctors from Beijing's leading hospitals measured blood
pressure and blood sugar for senior citizens, while legal and
health experts consulted them on their legal rights, health care,
and family well-being. A lecture was presented on the prevention
of age-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
In another development, State Councillor Peng Peiyun, who is in
charge of the women's and children's work at the State Council,
paid a visit to Beijing No.1 Social Welfare House and Beijing
Children's Welfare House, sending greetings and presents to the
elderly people and children there.
</P>
<P>
Respect for the elderly and caring for the young are important
in traditional Chinese morals. In the Warring State period more
than 2,000 years ago, Mencius, one of the most respected scholars
in Chinese history, preached that one should respect other's
elders just as one does one's own, and love others' children in
the same way.
</P>
<P>
In modern society, with an aging population and the increase of
split families, the well-being of the elderly and the young has
become even more important.
</P>
<P>
Throughout January, women's federations across China will
launch a variety of activities, including cooperating with local
media to run special newspaper editions or programs on TV and
radio to reinforce the theme. Other activities include urging
young and middle-aged couples to take better care of their
parents, help divorcing couples prepare for and adjust to life
after the separation, and aid children from poor families to
continue their education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
