<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Administrator on Failed Coup Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The alleged coup plot to
overthrow Nigeria's military regime was not uncovered by chance
but had been followed for at least one month before suspects were
arrested two weeks ago, a military administrator has revealed.
</P>
<P>
The government announced on December 21, 1997 the uncovery of
the coup plot and the arrest of 12 people involved, including the
country's number two person, Chief of General Staff Oladipo Diya
and two former ministers.
</P>
<P>
The coup plot was leaked by junior officers coopted into the
plan by the plotters about a month before the arrest, and the
government only tried to get more clues by delaying the action
till the day the coup was slated for execution, Oyo State
Administrator Ahmed Usman said.
</P>
<P>
The junior officers who leaked the coup plot were detained
afterwards to monitor the activities of the plotters closely and
record everything that transpired among them, he said, quoted by
the Daily Times today.
</P>
<P>
They at last submitted to the government 17 cassettes, both
audio and video, which showed the seriousness of the plot.
</P>
<P>
These electronic documentary materials have been shown to
military officers at the highest level, state administrators,
ministers and presentatives of traditional rulers across the
country.
</P>
<P>
These clips are expected to be available to the public, Usman
told members of the state council of Obas and top government
officials Friday in Ibadan, capital of the western state.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the plotters, confident that the arrangement
had not leaked, continued with the plans until the day of
execution when sporadic shooting began in some areas in the
capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers detailed to specific targets by the planners had
begun moving toward such targets when selected loyal officers
rounded them up, he said.
</P>
<P>
This shows it was not an attempted coup, it was at the
execution stage, he added.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the military touched on details of the
foiled coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
The administrator also dismissed claims that the alleged coup
plot has some ethnic background as most of the detainees are
Yorubas, people of one of the country's three main ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
It was only unfortunate that the present set largely consisted
of Yorubas from the west of the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, solidarity with the federal government over the
alleged coup plot has being intensified and rallies staged in
support of the administration of general Sany Abacha in many
parts of Nigeria in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
And human rights groups and some foreign countries, including
the United States, have called for fair, open trial of the
suspects.
</P>
<P>
With preliminary investigations already completed, a 15-member
special investigation board has been set up by the government to
decide the involvement of each of the detainees.
</P>
<P>
The special panel, formed at the end of last month, has one
month to carry out its mission before verdict is expected to be
brought in at court marshal or military tribunal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
