<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Close Five Military Attaches Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has decided to shut
down the offices of military attaches in five countries due to
shortage of foreign currency caused by the current financial
crisis, the Defense Ministry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The five countries are Venezuela, Greece, Austria, Myanmar and
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The nation will also delay its plan to establish offices of
military attaches in Ukraine and South Africa until its foreign
exchange situation is improved, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been sustaining a serious financial crisis
caused by the failure of some conglomerates and bad loans of
financial institution since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The nation's president-elect Kim Dae-jung, in his new year's
message on Thursday, appealed for national unity to overcome the
current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy, analysts said, could grind to halt
without speedy assistance from international financial
organizations and industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
However, the country, which is the 11th largest economy in the
world, has only received nine billion of the agreed rescue loans
totaling 57 billion U.S. dollars from the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, South Korea, with its foreign exchange reserve
reportedly standing at about nine billion U.S. dollars, has to pay
back roughly 25 billion U.S. dollars in foreign debts before
February. enditem
