<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 85th Indian Science Congress Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The 85th Indian science
congress opened Saturday at the Osmania University in Hyderabad
city, 1991 km south of New Delhi, to take stock of the successes
and failures in science over the past 50 years since the country's
independence in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral said in his inaugural speech
that top priority should be accorded to upgrading and extending
patents organizations to protect India's intellectual property
rights and meet stringent demands of the emerging world market.
</P>
<P>
Every technology denial by the West was converted into an
opportunity for Indian scientists. While meeting global
challenges, Indian scientists should also remember that there are
some problems typical to India like those of drinking water,
public hygiene, irrigation and optimum land use for habitation
which could only be solved by indigenous technologies, he said.
</P>
<P>
India should also participate in global research and
development programs to emerge as a global player, he further
said.
</P>
<P>
General president of the 85th Indian science congress Dr. P.
Rama Rao said that India needs several new measures and approaches
to revitalize its science infrastructure, including an increase in
annual research and development expenditure to two percent of
gross national product by the end of the ninth five-year plan
(1998-2002). Compared to global annual expenditure of 500 billion
US dollars on research and development, India's expenditure is
only 2.5 billion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
