<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda's Party Wants Him Back to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambian former president Kenneth
Kaunda's United National Independence Party (UNIP), the country's
biggest opposition party, wanted him back to prison because of
the "harsh conditions" that Kaunda has to meet under the current
house arrest.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail today quoted Kaunda's Press Aide Muhabi
Lungu as claiming here Friday that the conditions at the former
leader's home following his release from prison are "terrible and
inhuaman".
</P>
<P>
He charged that the conditions at Kaunda's house were "worse"
than those in the Mukobeko Prison in Kabwe, 120 kilometers north
of the capital, and warned that if things did not improve in the
near future, UNIP would rather have their "indomitable lion " in
jail.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who was put into Mukobeko Prison last December for
allegedly having involving in last October's abortive military
coup. He was later released from Prison and tranferred to house
arrest under a presidential order signed last Wednesday by
President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's house now is under heavy police care and is wire
fenced. He is banned to conduct political activities and to meet
the press.
</P>
<P>
During his detention in Mukobeko, said Lungu, Kaunda had all
sorts of visitors but now that he is at home, he can only be
allowed two visitors in a week and share 20 minutes with each
visitor. Only Kaunda's wife and grandchildren are allowed to live
with the "old man".
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 73, the father figure of the nation, led Zambia to
independence from the British colonial rule in 1964 and since
then he had ruled the country until 1991, when he was defeated by
incumbent President Chiluba in the country's general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
