<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Headquarters in Iraq Attacked by Grenades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The headquarters of the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq in Baghdad
was attacked Friday night by grenades, but nobody was injured,
according to local radio report today.
</P>
<P>
Two rocket-propelled grenades were fired late Friday at the
UNSCOM offices in Baghdad, the U.S. TV station Cable News Network
reported today.
</P>
<P>
No one was wounded in the attack and damage was minimal. A
grenade hit a wall and a window in the building's cafeteria was
shattered.
</P>
<P>
The guards at the UNSCOM headquarters' premises saw Friday
evening an explosion in the area facing the Canal Hotel where the
UNSCOM is based, the Iraqi News Agency quoted an Iraqi official as
saying today.
</P>
<P>
The guards inspected the site of the explosion but found no
damages.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authorities are investigating the incident to
identify the perpetrators of the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official blamed the attack on hostile parties that
seek to undermine the Iraqi-UNSCOM relations.
</P>
<P>
The attack was the second on U.N. offices in Baghdad in three
months.
</P>
<P>
One of the U.N. offices in Baghdad was attacked last October
and the Iraqi authorities arrested a number of suspects and
accused Iran of sponsoring the attack.
</P>
<P>
The attack Friday night, for which no one has claimed
responsibility, follows two months of tension between Iraq and the
United Nations over the weapons inspections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has refused access of U.N. weapons inspectors to Iraqi
Presidential palaces that U.N. arms inspectors doubted as covers
for Iraq's biological and chemical weapon programs.
</P>
<P>
But the United Nations has demanded that the U.N. inspectors
have access to the sites throughout Iraq which Baghdad has
declared off limits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
