<HEADLINE> Iraq Denounces Attack at UNSCOM Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today denounced the attack
Friday night at the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM)
headquarters at the Canal Hotel in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi spokesman slammed the attack as a sabotage aimed at
subverting the Iraq-UNSCOM relationship.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that security guards at the Canal Hotel
entrance on Friday night saw an explosion with columns of fire
in the across-the-street area, where most UNSCOM staff are
residing.
</P>
<P>
He added that the security guards made firsthand checking of
the source of the fire, without noting unusual activities.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authorities are investigating the incident to
identify the saboteurs, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UNSCOM officials found some components of two
unexploded shells, causing minimal damage to the parking lot and
shattering a window. So far no casualties have been reported.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM is responsible for verifying the disarmament of
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction. Until then will the
U.N. Security Council lift the crippling economic sanctions on
Iraq imposed in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The attack was the second on U.N. offices in Baghdad in three
months.
</P>
<P>
One of the U.N. offices in Baghdad was attacked last October
and the Iraqi authorities arrested a number of suspects and
accused Iran of sponsoring the attack.
</P>
<P>
The attack Friday night, for which no one has claimed
responsibility, follows two months of tension between Iraq and the
United Nations over the weapons inspections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has refused access of U.N. weapons inspectors to Iraqi
Presidential palaces that U.N. arms inspectors doubted as covers
for Iraq's biological and chemical weapon programs.
</P>
<P>
But the United Nations has demanded that the U.N. inspectors
have access to the sites throughout Iraq which Baghdad has
declared off limits. 
