<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Prisoners May Get House Arrest in Los Angeles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Los Angeles Police
Department (LAPD) is pushing forward with efforts to place
non-violent convicts on a house arrest program.
</P>
<P>
Police officials in this second largest U.S. city said they are
prepared to send up to 4,000 convicts home with electronic
monitoring bracelets, more than double the current number.
</P>
<P>
The measure is designed to free up jail beds and ensure that
more hardened convicts serve their full sentences behind bars.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that the average cost of incarceration is
between 45 to 65 U.S. dollars a day, the LAPD is under court order
to reduce its inmate population to cut cost.
</P>
<P>
The department said it has no choice but to return some
non-violent convicts -- many of them white-collar criminals -- to
the community through monitoring or work release.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are about 430 people out on work release and
about 1,500 on house arrest in the state of California, on the
U.S. west coast.
</P>
<P>
But critics question whether the police department has the
ability to adequately monitor activities of the inmates it places
on house arrest or work release.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, a Los Angeles municipal court judge ordered
the police department to put back behind bars a man sent home on
electronic monitoring after being convicted of stealing thousands
of dollars from business people who had sought his services.
</P>
<P>
The police department said it could take further steps to make
sure inmates stay out of trouble while on house arrest.
</P>
<P>
Since July, about 20 percent of the inmates placed on work
release have violated the terms of the program, compared to 9
percent placed on electronic monitoring. About two-thirds of the
violators in both programs have been returned to custody. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0091 </DOCNO>
