<HEADLINE> New Mexico, of U.S., Steps Up Airlift for Famished Herds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Six C-130 military cargo
planes dropped about 100 tons of food to herds stranded by heavy
snowstorms in eastern New Mexico, news reaching here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of New Mexico, in the U.S. west, were quoted as
saying that at least 5,000 animals have been killed by snowstorms
since Christmas Eve and that about 180,000 more are at risk.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit area is around the city of Roswell, where
ranchers have been unable to get feed to their herds. Reports said
some herds have not eaten during the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Another 115 tons of food will be dropped in the next two days
and the U.S. Agricultural Department agreed to reimburse ranchers
for up to 30 percent of the cost of buying food to be airlifted in.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of 1997, New Mexico ranchers had a total of
1.5 million beef cattle, 197,000 milk cows and 325,000 sheep.
</P>
