<HEADLINE> Iran's Freedom Movement Accused of Working for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian political party
Freedom Movement of Iran (FMI) was accused of working for the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), local newspaper Iran Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Friday prayer aggregation on the campus of
Tehran University, Mohammad Reza Faker, a Majlis (parliament)
member, threatened to "expose political figures" working for the
CIA.
</P>
<P>
"In the future at a press conference I will expose the names
of CIA agents (inside) Iran whose membership cards were shown (to
us) by the ambassador of the former Soviet Union to Tehran,"
Faker told the worshippers.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that an Iranian parliament member
launched such a stinging attack on the FMI and those affiliated
to the political party since it was founded in 1961 by former
Iranian prime minister Mehdi Bazargan.
</P>
<P>
The FMI has not been granted formal permission to carry out
activities since the country announced to register political
parties and organizations in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Faker stressed that "liberals and the Freedom Movement of Iran
had been ousted from the political mainstream" by the late
Iranian supreme leader Imam Khomeini and should no be allowed to
come back.
</P>
<P>
However, a FMI member rejected the accusation today in a
telephone interview with Xinhua, saying that it was not the first
time that the FMI was charged of "unfounded crimes."
</P>
<P>
Faker should provide necessary evidences to prove his
accusation against a political party, he said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of Iran's Freedom Movement Ebrahim Yazdi
was arrested on December 14 on charges of "desecrating religious
sanctities," but released on bail after a 10-day imprisonment.
</P>
</TEXT>
