<HEADLINE> Mid-China Region Improves Economic Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The middle part of China has
risen to become second only to the coastal regions in economic
growth, according to a report by the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) in mid-China -- made up of
Henan, Anhui, Hubei, Jiangxi and Hunan provinces -- grew at an
annual rate of 10.21 percent during 1979-1995, higher than the
national average of 9.89 percent, the report stated. The area has
maintained the same growth momentum.
</P>
<P>
The report went on to say that industrial growth spearheaded
the economic development of the region, with a rate that is about
one percent higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The report further noted that "four of the provinces have
actually edged into the top 10 with highest industrial growth,"
the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading capital construction projects in the
region help promote its economic growth, citing as examples the
construction of the Three Gorges hydropower project on the Yangtze
River, the Xiaolangdi hydropower station on the Yellow River and
the Beijing-Kowloon Railway, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
