</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market, this New Year holiday-shortened
week saw January South end 100 ringgit (25.6 U.S. dollars) better
at 2,150 ringgit (551.2 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to maintain its upside potential next
week but this could be affected by intermittent technical
corrections, a dealer said, adding that the ringgit's movement
will continue to be a major factor in determining the cash
market's direction.
</P>
<P>
Buying activity is expected to intensify, if the ringgit
declines further after easing to 3.9250/50 against the U.S. dollar
on Friday, the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that demand for crude palm oil would remain
favorable, evident from the expectation of higher export figures
estimated for December by private forecaster Caleb Brett.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the week, the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), which
was closed on Wednesday and Thursday for the New Year, also
closed higher with the metal gaining 14 sen to end at 20.24
ringgit (5.18 U.S. dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover was relatively high at 288 tons despite
trading for three days only this week against 249 tons last week
with European, local and Japanese traders accounting for the
week's transactions.
</P>
<P>
The price differential between the KLTM and that of the London
Metal Exchange (LME) was at a discount of 128 U.S. dollars per ton
on Friday against a premium of 30 U.S. dollars per ton previously.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM is expected to see higher tin prices on fresh buying
support next week as players return to the market after their long
vacation.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said demand should improve next week with the coming
back of foreign traditional buyers, especially from Europe, who
have abstained from the market since the tail-end of December.
</P>
<P>
But, the Malaysian rubber market this week was mixed. January
RSS One decreased three sen to 273.50 sen (70.1 U.S. cents) per kg
from last week's close at 276.50 sen (70.8 U.S. cents) while SMR
20 was up two sen at 274.00 sen (70.2 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment on the local rubber market is expected to remain
mixed next week against a backdrop of poor fundamentals and an
absence of players who are still away for the New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
The rubber market is only expected to pick up in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
