<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) closed the week stronger on Saturday due to what
dealers said year-end window dressing by local institutions.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE market saw some gains being made in the first three
days of the week prior to the New Year holiday on Thursday, but
the momentum was not sustained when the market reopened for
trading on Friday, the first trading day in the New Year, as
evident from the sharp decline in share prices.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the benchmark Composite Index rose 21 points
to end the week at 571.96 against 550.96 last week, the all Main
Board Emas Index gained 2.25 points to closed the week at 146.27
from last week's close at 144.02, the Industrial Index added 1.67
points to 1,093.33 while the Second Board Index lost 6.23 points
to 154.11.
</P>
<P>
Apart from interest on the usual blue-chip counters like
Telekom, Tenaga National and Maybank, which helped boost the
index, focus was also centered on finance stocks during the week.
</P>
<P>
Late on Friday, Gadek Capital announced that it had obtained
approval from the State Bank to negotiate a merger with Credit
Corporation (Malaysia) Bhd and EON Finance, two finance companies
within the DRB-HICOM group.
</P>
<P>
There were also rumors circulating in the market that
Malaysia's biggest bank, Malayan Banking Bhd may be merged with
Bank Bumiputera Malaysia Bhd.
</P>
<P>
The week's grand total turnover covering all markets stood at
830 million shares valued at 2,272.422 million ringgit (about
582.672 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the main board, the week's volume dropped to 554.892 million
shares valued at 1.426 billion ringgit (about 365.641 million
dollars) from 492.832 million stocks worth 1.023 billion ringgit
(about 262.307 million dollars) trade last week.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 27.887 million shares traded on
the main board, industrial products 45.963 million shares,
construction 32.309 million shares, trade/services 123.882 million
shares, infrastructure 3.836 million shares, finance 161.665
million shares, hotels 2.722 million shares, properties 64.791
million shares, plantation 38.167 million shares, mining 3.799
million shares, trusts 1.712 million shares, closed/funds 882,000
shares, loans 19.805 million shares and TSR/warrants 27.472
million shares.
</P>
<P>
On the second board, volume declined to 55.281 million shares
valued at 129.970 million ringgit (about 33.325 million dollars)
from 64.114 million shares worth 119.083 million ringgit (about
30.534 million dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals, however, increased to 219.826 million shares
valued at 715.470 million ringgit (about 183.453 million dollars)
from 83.100 million shares worth 498.437 million ringgit (about
127.804 million dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The most active counter was Tenaga Nasional with 27.389 million
shares traded valued at 217.989 million ringgit (about 55.894
million dollars) and the counter gained 25 sen to end the week at
7.65 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Other counters among the top ten this week included IOI
Corporation, MBf Capital, Telekom, Maybank, Commerce Assets, RHB
Capital, John Hancock, AMMB and Arab-Malaysian Finance - Foreign.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that no cheer or celebration was expected on the
KLSE, at least in the early part of next week, as the continuing
weak ringgit which ended at 3.95 ringgit against the U.S. dollar
on Friday and rising interest rates is envisaged to further dampen
the market's prevailing bearish sentiment.
</P>
<P>
State Bank's announcement that maximum base lending rate for
both commercial banks and finance companies will be raised to
10.45 percent and 12.3 percent respectively is also expected to
hurt finance stocks, they said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark 100-company Composite Index, is already showing
resistance at the 540 points level but if this hurdle is breached
the next strong support level could be pegged at the 500 points
level, the said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
