<HEADLINE> Two Million People Lose Jobs in Indonesia During </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- More than two million people
have lost their jobs since the monetary crisis began last July in
the country, according to estimates by the Indonesian Armed Forces
(ABRI).
</P>
<P>
ABRI spokesman Brig. Gen. A. Wahab Mokodongan said on Friday
that such a crisis could destabilize the country, especially when
people were easily provoked by speculation and rumors.
</P>
<P>
However, ABRI members are ready to crack down on any
"security-disturbing activities," Wahab said.
</P>
<P>
Now in the middle of the worst ever monetary crisis, the
country is preparing for the five-yearly general meeting of the
People's Consultative Assembly next March, which will elect a
president and a vice president and also endorse the State Policy
Guidelines for 1998/2003.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the accuracy of his estimations, Wahab said:
"It was based on reports that many companies and industries had
recently laid off their workers."
</P>
<P>
However, the head of the Jakarta Chamber of Commerce and
Industry, Julia Hasan, said last week that 2.4 million workers had
lost their jobs in Jakarta and the surrounding towns.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have warned that the unemployment rate would rise to
11 percent in 1997 from seven percent of the total 90
million-strong work force in the country in 1995 as companies
struggle with big debts in foreign currencies, despite a
multi-billion dollar economic rescue package put together by the
International Monetary Fund IMF).
</P>
<P>
At the end of last October, the IMF agreed to provide a 23
billion dollar long-term loan to Indonesia to help the country
overcome the current monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Indonesian rupiah has lost more than 100
percent against the U.S. dollar since early July last year. Many
small and medium-sized factories and companies, badly hit by the
currency crisis, have reduced their production and laid off
workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
