<HEADLINE> Panama's Tariff Cut Draws Criticism From Enterprisers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian
Industrialists Syndicate (SIP) reiterated here Friday that the
tariff cut implemented by the government will affect at least 71
percent of the country's enterprises in 1998.
</P>
<P>
If this continues, SIP members said, it is possible that many
local firms will be affected in four or five months.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government decreed January 1 a reduction of
tariffs. All the products formerly tariffed between 5.1 to 14.9
percent will now have a tax rate of 10 percent, and those above 15
percent will be lowered to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The other tariff levels are 3 and 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dario Selles, president of the Panamanian Exporters
Association, said the new law will hit hard some of the country's
productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, "The law will not include dairy products,
whose tax rate was reduced from 50 percent to 40 percent, rice,
which saw its tariff down from 60 percent to 30 percent, and motor
vehicles, which go up from 15 percent to 20 percent."
</P>
<P>
This hasty drop in tariffs, Selles said, will simply create a
serious problem for the Panamanian industries, because
entrepreneurs will have no time to prepare for the sudden
changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
