<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economic Downturn Blamed for Rise in Court Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of civil and criminal
lawsuits in Thailand increased sharply last year, with many of
them related to the country's economic downturn, according to the
Nation newspaper Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The total number of civil cases reached 280,000 in 1997,
compared to 193,000 in the previous year, with 27 percent of the
cases related to loans and 24.3 percent to leases.
</P>
<P>
The remaining cases included bad checks, breaches of purchase
contracts and bankruptcy. There were about 3,000 bankruptcy cases
in 1997, compared to only 500 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Civil Court Chief Justice Pheng Phengniti said the figures
would rise this year as there are many expected breach-of-contract
cases where purchasers could not come up with payment for their
orders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, compared with 1996, criminal cases in 1997 increased
by nearly 10,000 per month to reach a total of 560,000. There were
443,500 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Crime is also likely to rise this year as a result of the
growing unemployment problem, the newspaper said, quoting criminal
court Chief Justice Pradit Ekmanee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
