<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Reaffirms Sovereignty Over Malvinas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine government
Friday reaffirmed its unquestionable sovereignty over Islas
Malvinas (Falklands) and the surrounding waters.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement released on the eve of 165th anniversary
of Britain's occupation of Islas Malvinas (Falklands), the
Argentine government said it is determined to regain its
sovereignty through peaceful negotiations in accordance with the
Constitution and international demands.
</P>
<P>
Argentina will seek a just and thorough settlement of the
dispute with Britain, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine government is committed to respect the life style
of Malvinas (Falklands) islanders and to promote the exchanges and
cooperation between the island and mainland residents, it added.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem, due to visit London later
this year, said recently that he would discuss with British
leaders the issue of shared Malvinas (Falklands) sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Menem will be the first Argentine president to visit Britain
since the Malvinas (Falklands) War in 1982.
</P>
<P>
However, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook later ruled out
the possibility of shared sovereignty without the agreement of
local residents.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Argentine Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella described
Cook's remarks as "no surprise," saying Britain "never hopes to
hold substantive negotiations" with Argentina on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Islas Malvinas (Falklands), located on the southern Atlantic
Ocean, was occupied by Britain on January 3, 1833. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
