<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Falls to 6,200 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Sustained corporate demand for
U.S. dollars brought the Indonesian rupiah down to 6,200 against
the greenback Friday, while share prices at the Jakarta Stock
Exchange rose by two percent, dealers and brokers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers said corporate dollar buying to pay
dollar-denominated debts remained high in the market, pushing the
local currency further down on Friday, the first trading day of
the new year.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah was quoted at 6,000/6,200 at 6:00 p.m. local time,
the lowest since the currency was floated in August last year.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts blamed the indebted corporating for the sharp
depreciation of the rupiah against the dollar on Friday. The
rupiah has lost more than 100 percent of its value against the
dollar since last July.
</P>
<P>
The government has said Indonesia's private offshore debts
total 65 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 55 percent of the
country's total debts of 118 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
AS the rupiah weakened, stock prices on the Jakarta Stock
Exchange gained 2.07 percent, with the composite index rising 8.29
points to close at 410.01.
</P>
<P>
Stockbrokers said the market opened 1998 trading with an
expectation of a better 1998-99 state budget to be announced by
President Soeharto on January 6.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
