<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Population Reduced in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Currently, 71 percent of the
Chinese citizens are farmers, as against the formerly established
some 80 percent, due to industrialization in rural areas since the
country launched reforms in late 1970s, According to Beijing-based
"China Daily" today.
</P>
<P>
The result was based on a random survey on 40,576 rural
households across China.
</P>
<P>
Among agricultural families, 62.81 percent live on their land
and 30.57 percent have some income from outside agriculture. For
6.62 percent, farming is no longer the main source of income.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also found that the proportion of households
depending on agriculture is lowest in the coastal provinces,
greater in mid-China and highest in the land-locked western area.
</P>
<P>
During China's reform process, farmers began to diversify their
trades to enlarge their earnings. Township enterprises were one of
their best inventions.
</P>
<P>
These operations absorb most rural labour. There were 1,396,300
non-agricultural township enterprises by the end of 1996,
employing 52.96 million people. Over 55 percent of township
enterprises are located in eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
Most of these firms specialize in industrial manufacturing,
construction, transportation, catering trade, retailing and other
service sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
