<HEADLINE> Thailand to Launch Campaign for Consumers' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will launch
a campaign aimed at educating Thai people about the rights of
consumers, the local press reported on Saturday, quoting deputy
prime minister Suvit Khunkitti.
</P>
<P>
Suvit said the government would also encourage students and
housewives to set up consumer protection groups in their campuses
and their respective communities, in line with Tuesday's cabinet
resolution declaring 1998-99 as years of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
The responsibility for protecting consumer's rights should not
be left with the government alone, but should also be extended to
the consumers themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
As Thailand is trying to gain a share of the tourism business
from other areas such as Hong Kong and Singapore, the campaign
would convince foreign tourists that they would not be cheated if
they buy products in Thailand, he said.  
</P>
