<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deficit Ratio to GDP Falls to 2.7 percent in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Italy's deficit accounted for 2.7
percent of its gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997, compared to
the 3 percent criteria required for the single European currency,
the Euro, the Treasury Ministry said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, the borrowing requirement for the
past year should come out at about 52.5 trillion lire (30 billion
U.S. dollars), compared with the government's projection of 68
trillion lire (38 billion U.S. dollars) and the previous year's
figure of 128.9 trillion lire (73 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This will probably be the second time in 17 years that the
country's spending budget be respected. In 1986, the government's
spending cost was 750 billion lire (428 million dollars) below the
figure originally planned.
</P>
<P>
Though final figures for Italy's GDP in 1997 won't be available
until February, the International Monetary Fund also suggested
that Italy's deficit ratio to GDP would at best only scrape inside
the 3-percent limit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
