<HEADLINE> Venezuela, Chile Adopt Bilateral Zero Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela and Chile have signed
a trade agreement to lift all customs tariffs beginning in 1998 in
an effort to promote bilateral trades.
</P>
<P>
With the zero tariffs adopted on January 1 of this year, the
commercial integration between Venezuela and Chile is a reality,
Venezuelan authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement affected Venezuelan chemical and
petrochemical products and Chilean agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, Venezuela and Chile have put in force some free
trade agreements, but the elimination of the last customs tariffs
was negotiated until the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The removal of all import duties will increase trade between
the two countries this year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade volume reached 320 million U.S. dollars in
1996 and 360 million dollars in 1997, respectively, only a modest
increase despite the growing trend of commercial liberalizations
between them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
