<HEADLINE> Tennis legend Helen Wills Moody Dies at 92 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Eight-time Wimbledon champion
Helen Wills Moody of the United States has died at 92 in Carmel of
California.
</P>
<P>
The hard-hitting tennis star, who died Thursday at Carmel
Convalescent Hospital, had won eight Wimbledon singles titles
during the 1920s and '30s and hold the the record for 52 years
until Martina Navratilova broke it in the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
Moody won 31 major titles, including seven U.S. Opens and four
French Opens.
</P>
<P>
She hit the ball harder than anyone she faced, slamming both
forehand and backhand shots the full length of the court. Moody
won her first U.S. women's tournament in 1923 and retired after
winning at Wimbledon in 1938.
</P>
<P>
She had no survivors. Her ashes will be scattered at sea. No
service will be held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
