<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Planners Build Insurance for Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The China Family Planning
Association (CFPA), the country's largest non-governmental
organization, will expand social insurance benefits in rural areas
for households practising family planning.
</P>
<P>
The strategy is to maintain previous birth control achievements
and remove worries about how people will manage in their old age, a
CFPA official said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Jin Hongmei, CFPA director of social insurance affairs, is
quoted by today's China Daily as saying that the association, with
support from some state departments, would take measures to ensure
social insurance benefits related to family planning be continued
steadily.
</P>
<P>
The insurances will be made an important component of
the country's family planning work, Jin noted.
</P>
<P>
First initiated in Liaoning and Fujian provinces in 1985, a
series of social insurance benefits have been set up in 31
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, said Jin.
</P>
<P>
They include health insurance for an only child and mother, and
pension insurance for rural parents with one boy or two
girls. Family planning workers receive life and property insurance.
</P>
<P>
Families benefited will shoulder only a small proportion of the
cost of the insurance service, with the majority shared by the
central and local government and local township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Children who are insured may get compensation for medical
charges when they are ill; with pension insurance, parents may get
a monthly payment to live on when they reach the age of 60.
</P>
<P>
Data form the CFPA further showed that over 45 million people
have joined the various insurance schemes, which have an
accumulated fund of four billion yuan (481 million U.S. dollars);
about 30 percent is pension insurance for rural couples who
practise family planning.
</P>
<P>
About 85-90 percent of the schemes are established through
insurance companies, the rest through banks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
