<HEADLINE> Karpov Wins Opener over Anand in World Chess Champ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia's defending world chess
champion Anatoly Karpov won the opening game against challenger
Viswanathan Anand in the World Chess Championship finals in
Lausanne, Switzerland, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Karpov, playing white pieces, battled more than six and a half
hours against his 28-year-old Indian opponent, who beat Michael
Adams of England in an eliminator in December to win the challenge
right.
</P>
<P>
Karpov somewhat surprised Anand in a theoretical novelty move
in the semi-slav defense, Meran variation, that involves a knight
sacrifice on move 17.
</P>
<P>
Six games are scheduled in the finals, organized by the
International Chess Federation (FIDE), with a possible tie-break
to decide the title on January 9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
