<DOCNO> XIE19980103.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dealers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso may go down
further to 45 against the U.S. dollar after it tumbled to a
historic low on Friday, dealers here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the peso plunged to a historic new low of 41.80 to
the dollar from 39.90 on the last day of trading in 1997 on
corporate dollar demand and continued pressure from the weakness
of regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian ringgit was lower at 3.92/3.93 on Friday compared
with 3.86/3.87 on New Year's Eve, while the Indonesian rupiah was
weaker at 5,800/6,000 as against the previous 5,000/5,100.
</P>
<P>
"Our currency cannot remain strong when the others in the
region are sliding. Our exports cannot compete anymore. We just
have to go with the Asian currencies," the Manila Times quoted
Pedro Florecio, president of Foreign Exchange Association of the
Philippines, as saying on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It could go over 45. It would be new territory," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso has lost 36.8 percent of its value against
the dollar since it started to fall on July 11.
</P>
<P>
The pressure on the peso has remained even after the central
bank promised to make available non-deliverable forwards (NDFs)
this month.
</P>
<P>
The NDFs will provide those firms with unhedged foreign
exchange exposures an option to buy dollar without crowding the
spot foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
But bankers said clients may not use the NDF facility if the
pricing is expensive.
</P>
<P>
"It depends on the perception of clients whether the rate being
quoted is acceptable or not," said a dealer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
