<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Infantile Mortality Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The infantile mortality reduced
in Cuba from 7.9 per thousand born alive in 1996, to 7.2 per
thousand in 1997, the official daily newspaper Granma today quoted
the country's health authorities as saying.
</P>
<P>
Other indexes that also registered drops were the under five
mortality, 9.3 per one thousand born alive, mothers' death rate
during labor, 2.2 per 10,000, as well as low weight at birth, 6.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The world average of the infantile mortality is 60 per one
thousand born alive, similar to the one registered in Cuba before
the taking over by the socialist government in 1959.
</P>
<P>
These public health achievements put Cuba among the 25
countries with the best index of attention to the mother and the
child. 
</P>
</TEXT>
