<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homicide Rate Drops in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The number of reported
murders in Washington D.C. fell from 397 in 1996 to 301 in 1997,
the lowest figure in 10 years, a senior police officer said here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference, Sonya Proctor, the acting police
chief in the capital of the United States, attributed the drop of
the homicide rate to the strengthened police patrol on city
streets.
</P>
<P>
Proctor was appointed interim chief of the 3,800-officer
department after the unexpected resignation of Larry Soulsby in
November.
</P>
<P>
Proctor said there's no question that Washington D.C. has
become a better place for people to live and visit.
</P>
<P>
"Crime is down and is down by a significant percentage.
Homicides are down," she added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said homicides were down last year from Los
Angeles to New York City as big cities across America put more
emphasis on high-profile neighborhood police patrols.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years, the number of murders in Washington
reached the high of 489 in 1991 when the city was dubbed the
"murder capital of America." 
</P>
</TEXT>
