<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pupils Having Less Pressure with Their Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Some Beijing pupils are no
longer worried about taking their exams before the month-long
winter vacation starts in mid-January, according to today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Homework and scores won't bother you any more," said Cai Fang,
a pupil at a primary school in Haidian District in northwest
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
It was an educational reform initiated September 1997 that has
made the exams less awe-inspiring for thousands of pupils in the
district.
</P>
<P>
The reform means abandoning the use of scores to define the
result of the exam. Instead, pupils' final achievements will be
graded as "excellent, good, pass and fail" with 40 percent based
on their exam scores and 60 percent on daily performance.
</P>
<P>
The reform replaced the 100-mark system which has been used for
about 40 years. Moreover, it has reduced homework by half.
</P>
<P>
About a quarter, or 106,000 of Beijing's pupils are among the
first to say goodbye to the old system.
</P>
<P>
Yet many parents do not like the present practice, worrying
that their children may become wild and lazy without the pressure
of scores.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Xu Xiuru, an expert form the National Institute of
Healthy Education, said: "Many parents have ignored the fact that
most things kids can do now, thanks to the reform, are related and
beneficial to their study, and, more importantly to the development
of their potential."
</P>
<P>
Educational departments were persuaded to try out the reform
package in Shanghai in 1991 by educators who maintain it is
necessary to free students from the grip of the score-oriented
100-system.
</P>
<P>
Xu noted that the number of pupils who suffer form mental
problems due to the pressure of homework and fierce competition
under the 100-mark system has increased over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
So far, the reform has been introduced to primary schools in
Beijing, Tianjin, and the provinces of Shangdong, Jiangsu and
Liaoning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
