<HEADLINE> Colombia Controls Inflation in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Colombia closed 1997
with a 17.9 percent inflation compared to the 18 percent forecast
by the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The inflation drop was attributed to the control of the prices
in education and public services, to the low cost of imported
goods, and to the economic recession and its negative effects on
the demand, according to bank sources.
</P>
<P>
However, it will be difficult to achieve this year the control
of the inflation because the authorities cannot control
further prices and the recession, said the sources. 
