<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mergers Valued at Record 1.63 Trillion Dlrs in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide mergers and
acquisitions surged 48 percent to a record value of 1.63 trillion
U.S. dollars in 1997, according to statistics of a private U.S.
research firm.
</P>
<P>
The figure for 1996 was 1.1 trillion dollars, said New
Jersey-based Securities Data Co. in its latest report.
</P>
<P>
U.S. mergers amounted to 919 billion dollars in 1997, compared
to 626 billion dollars in 1996, thanks to its strong economy and
favorable stock market.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 saw megadeals in financial services and
telecommunications such as the 25 billion dollar merger of the
U.S. Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corp., and the 37
billion dollar merger of WorldCom Inc. and MCI Communications
Corp. in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Analysts see the merger growth trend, which started six years
ago, to continue as a result of on-going globalization and
technological changes when corporations want to do big strategic
transactions.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street executives suggest that 1998 could be another
strong year to see new deals in financial services and
telecommunications sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
