<HEADLINE> Action Urged to Deal With Kurdish Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Greece today urged Schengen
Treaty member states to coordinate their action in order to tackle
the growing illegal immigration of Kurds into western Europe.
</P>
<P>
Stelios Perrakis, secretary-general of the Greek Foreign
Ministry, said in statements that the rise in the flow of illegal
immigrants to Europe, particularly to the European Union (EU)
countries, had in the last few months caused concern and mobilized
the interest of EU organs and of Schengen.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the causes of the illegal immigration to the
"aggressive Turkish military activity in northern Iraq and
Turkey's policy not to control or restrict, and even tolerate the
flow of Iraqi refugees through its territory westwards."
</P>
<P>
The general-secretary stressed that the issue could not be
dealt with through increased police measures and stricter control
of external borders, but through coordinated action by Schengen
countries.
</P>
<P>
All Schengen countries must demand of Turkey the signing of an
agreement for re-entry, he added.
</P>
<P>
As for what action Greece will take to deal with the problem,
he said that on the one hand, Greece would tackle the refugees'
applications for asylum in the framework of its obligations
arising from the 1951 Geneva Convention on the status of refugees
and from the international law, and on the other hand, Greece
would take all necessary measures to control its external borders.
</P>
<P>
Greece has been watching closely the developments and has
increased patrols by coastguard and navy vessels to check the
ships transporting illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Foreign Ministry will also decide within this month
the additional measures in accordance with the Schengen Treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
