<HEADLINE> Big Mergers Likely to Continue in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Big company mergers and
acquisitions will continue to be caught in newspaper headlines in
1998 after a record 1.2023 trillion U.S. dollar worth of deals
were announced the past year.
</P>
<P>
The mergers and acquisitions involving U.S. firms last year
accounted for 915 billion U.S. dollars -- up almost 50 percent on
the previous record of 626 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, according
to newspaper reports here.
</P>
<P>
The increased amount helped adjust economic structures and
production layout of the world.
</P>
<P>
Mega-mergers catching the public attention included WorldCom's
pending 41.8 billion U.S. dollar purchase of MCI and Boeing's 16.3
billion U.S. dollars acquisition of McDonnell Douglas, are set to
continue.
</P>
<P>
Big mergers and acquisitions are powered by a need for
strategic partners to compete in the global economy, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
Plenty of action is still to come in financial services,
telecommunications, health care, defense and utility industries.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts regarded mergers and acquisitions as a cyclical
business, which can end overnight, as it did suddenly a few years
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
