<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Open Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A late rally brought stocks on
Wall Street higher in the first session of 1998, helped by some
encouraging economic news that sent interest rates to a new 4-year
low in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose about 56.79 points to
7,965.04, with most of that gain coming over the final hour.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 366.20 million shares as
against 465.78 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.61 to 975.04, less
than 9 points from record terrain; and the NYSE composite index
rose 0.96 to 512.15, about two points shy of a new closing high.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 11.17 to 1,581.52, but the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies slipped 0.50 to 436.52,
and the American Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.07 to
682.54.
</P>
<P>
Bonds rose amid news that the manufacturing sector's growth
rate slowed in December.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices rose, the yield on the 30-year Treasury fell to
5.84 percent, the lowest point since October 1993.
</P>
<P>
Trading was heavy in telecommunications stocks following late
Wednesday's surprise ruling by a federal judge that gave
regional phone companies an unobstructed path to compete in the
80 billion U.S. dollar long-distance market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
